segments.text: Today's date is July 17th, July 18th, July 19th, testing, testing, this is a test, this is a test, testing, testing, by getting some back... That we'll have to live with.
Yeah, that's fine.
Oh, wait a minute.
Today is July 18th, 1985.
I'm talking to Officer Teal.
What's your first name?
John.
John Teel, T-E-E-L, about who is an officer on the UC police force.
And I want to start off by talking a little bit about your background.
Where and when were you born?
When did you start with a police force?
JOHN TEEL, I was born in Kansas.
I'm 57 years old.
I've been here in California since I was 9.
I have been here on the campus since 1959.
Okay.
So could you tell me a little bit about the training and the police force in 1959 and how it's changed since today?
In 1959, they gave you a gun, a flashlight, and a map, and keys to the building, and said, go out there and do it.
And they didn't give you any formalized training?
None.
None?
None.
How about today?
Today it's so formalized that it is almost bordering on FBI standards, I would say.
Really?
And where did UC get these standards?
I mean, where did they derive them from?
Well, all the police departments within the state of California belong to the police officer standard of training post.
They all have a school.
We have schools that are 16 weeks old, or long.
16 weeks long, yeah.

And after they go through a rigorous program on self-defense, how to subdue people without hurting them, the use of your nightstick, the use of radios, traffic laws, rules, regulations, then they come back here.
to us after 16 weeks in training.
And they are put with a training officer for another 16 weeks.
Like a senior officer on the force?
A senior officer on the force or an officer that has been
No, it has to be an officer that's been to the officer's training school with four training rookies.
And that's 16 weeks, and after 16 weeks, he's then evaluated and either let go or retained.
Now, why did this formalization, why did this school, rules and regulations, why did it come about?
Well, it was just one of the things it had to be.
Prior to POST, every department had their own little thing going.
Yeah.
Oakland has its own police academy, which is probably one of the best in California or the United States.
San Francisco has another one.
Los Angeles has their own.
The smaller departments can't afford them.
Sure.
So they go to various places.
We have one out in
Near Antioch, we have another one in Chico and one in Sacramento.
Sometimes we use the Highway Patrol Academy.
And that's it.
And did it have anything to do with the riots in the 1960s, do you think?
Probably had everything to do with it.
Could you explain that?
We didn't even have radios at the time.
The larger departments did.
We had maybe four radios.
When the riots broke out, we had 28 officers.
What's the size of the force today?
Oh, it's only 65, but we went to 108.
My goodness, that's good information.
Okay, when were you at 108?
During the peak of the riots.
I'd say, what, up to 19... Naples Park, 1969, something like that.
Yeah.
Okay.
Oh, okay.
Now, how about...
The emphasis, has the emphasis as far as training officers changed?
I don't understand the question.
Has, has, well, obviously the type of training has changed, but I mean the emphasis on the type of tactics that you'd use in certain situations or the type of people that you'd recruit.
Oh, well, the recruitment is still a high school education, clear background.
and physical agility test, psychological test.
Then they go in for, it's not so much, it's still self-defense for yourself in any situation, but you're taught how to take somebody down without hurting them.
It's becoming more of a, almost a verbal confrontation now instead of the old times you used to
get in an argument real quick, and it was knocked down and dragged out.
Not to that effect, but it's that opposed from what we were doing as what we're doing now.
Where the victim is, we're taught that the victim still has lots of rights and needs to be treated with respect, and that's it.
And when about, do you remember when these rules and regulations first started?
I'm trying to remember back, probably 60...
No, let's see.
We instituted our own police academy.
I don't remember what year it was.
Here on our own campus, we had people come to it from Berkeley, Albany, Rad Lab.
And while we were there attending our school up at the football stadium, in the press box, they blew up the electrical transmission line up
Centennial Road.
Oh, okay.
And I think that was in 67?
I'm not sure of the date.
Yeah, I can check that out.
Yeah.
And then it was after that.
Was it after that that they decided to?
No, that's when they started it.
Okay.
Okay.
They started to get a more formalized training?
More formalized training.
That's also, we had a new chief.
Oh, okay, so... Chief Beal.
Okay, who was the old chief?
Woodward was the old chief.
Woodward?
He was an old-timer.
He was a good man.
He thought and... Do you remember his first name?
Frank Woodward.
Okay.
And he was a wonderful person.
And...
He was in law enforcement his whole life, but his law enforcement was an entirely different phase than we have to accept today.
Chief Beale came.
He was a... What's his first name?
William.
Okay.
He came to us from Berkeley.
He retired from Berkeley, police department.
But he had been to the FBI academies.
He had been to, my God, I don't know.
He had his Ph.D. in a...
In criminology, he did?
Oh, yeah.
And the dissidents always claimed that Chief Beale did not have to carry a gun.
He was armed with words at least four inches long.
We would have followed him into a fire.
That's what we thought of him.
And so it was his idea, along with the general campus unrest and this particular blowing up some power lines,
Well, the power lines had nothing to do with it.
That was just a year that I remember that we were in school.
Oh, okay.
But it was his idea to formalize the police training?
Yes.
And his, actually, it was his starting it that we were up at our own academy.
He had started that even then.
Oh, okay.
What other changes did he decide to bring about?
Jurisdictional changes.
With Berkeley, we would take care of our own property no matter where it's located.
We'd have full control of it, working towards.
Well, how was it before that?
The only thing, we had a golden ring, so to speak, around the university.
You didn't step across that ring.
Yeah.
OK. And that ring was like the border of the university?
That was the border of the university.
Hearst, Bancroft, Piedmont, and Oxford.
OK, and the outlining areas that the university owned, like the People's Park area.
The People's Park.
The Berkeley police would take care of that before?
We always had that.
We had that all the time.
Because that was right here.
It was when they started bringing the dormitories in, lying off campus.
We have property out in Albany now, Living Students Group.
We have the Richmond Field Station.
Oh, God, we've got people everywhere.
I mean, property everywhere.
And that's probably one reason for an increasing number of police on the force.
No, that had nothing to do with the force.
The reason they increased the force is because we needed them for bodies for protecting the university campus during the riots.
Okay, okay.
Any other changes that Beale brought about?
No, there's so many different things that he'd done.
that he's almost, it's hard to say what he didn't do.
It's easier to say that he didn't do this than it would be to tell you what he did do.
Okay, then how did the relationships with the student radicals change once he came in?
They're still radical.
Yeah.
I mean, there was no change in them except you'd...
I mean, the relationship between the police and the student radicals.
I don't think there was any change.
They still think the way they do.
And we listen to them more than we used to.
Maybe that's a change, a good change.
We, in turn, really don't have a heck of a lot to do with them, because that all was handed through the chancellor's office, or supposed to be.
OK, let's talk a little bit about the first
riot or confrontation that you were in.
Was that the free speech movement in 64?
Didn't we have one prior to that?
No, that was the first major one.
That was the first one, yeah.
That was the first major one in the fall of 1964.
And that started all over a four-letter word that was posted at Van Croft and Telegraph.
A guy was holding the sign up.
Oh, that was the filthy speech.
That came in.
It's the same thing.
Same thing.
Okay, okay.
And it started from there to where now they have Sproul Plaza, which is a free speech area.
Almost anything goes.
It's hard for anyone to be insulted on Sproul Plaza.
I believe the courts has found that people can walk away from it if they don't like it.
Well, when did that come about, where they made it a free speech plaza?
That's when it started.
Oh, okay, okay.
And gradually it just worked up, even up until today, you know.
Yeah, right.
And I've, you know, everyone's been out there before, and occasionally, you know, someone will insult police officers.
How do you deal with that?
I'm not even going to talk to you about it.
Oh, okay.
Okay.
What was your job?
What were your responsibilities back about 1964 and 65 during the free speech movement?
PATROLLING, TRYING TO TAKE THE PARK BACK.
GENERAL, JUST GENERAL POLICE WORK.
OKAY.
AND WERE YOU INVOLVED THEN WITH THE PEOPLE'S PARK?
OH, SURE.
OKAY.
COULD YOU TELL ME ABOUT THAT?
IT WAS VERY SIMPLE.
WE TOOK IT AWAY FROM THEM, AND THEY TOOK IT AWAY FROM US.
FINALLY, THEY GAVE IT UP, AND WE GOT IT BACK, ONLY THEY NOW CONTROL IT.
NOW, YOU FIGURE THAT ONE OUT.

what does that do to morale on the police force it's the shits and uh who would you who would you or where would you play not who but where would you place a responsibility i'm not placing responsibility anywhere that's not my job oh okay can you tell me about the uh cooperation uh
between the Berkeley police, the National Guard, and UC police?
Totally 100% cooperation.
Okay, well, can you tell me about the dynamics?
I mean, who is in charge, and how do you deal when you have three separate forces like that?
We had five, six, we probably had 20 different forces.
We had highway patrol, city police, army, highway patrol.
At that time, the sheriff's

is the person that takes over okay okay so the sheriff's in charge of the chain of command at that time it's automatically his because it's in his county and that's california law it's california law you know i'd be that's kind of surprising because i would have thought that probably the national guard general would have taken over uh because he's a direct line to the governor we were telling the national guard general what to do i had a
I don't know, a lieutenant colonel or a colonel or something.
And we were standing at University House.
And here comes a couple of thousand demonstrators, and he'd run over to me, my God, officer, what are we going to do?
I said, stand up.
And we did, and he didn't know what to do.
But that's National Guard.
I mean, that's not their primary purpose is not keeping order.
Yeah, exactly.
They were quartered in People's Park.
We had a fence around it.
And a number of the dissidents got together and they sent some very beautiful young ladies down to the park and gave them cookies.
It turned out that they were laced with LSD and marijuana.
So we don't take cookies from strange people.
Tell me some of the other tactics that were used against you.
Yesterday you said that there were real long slingshots.
Could you tell me some of the weapons and tactics that were used?
Well, they had long surgical tube slingshots for throwing rocks, and if they got a hold of one of our grenades that still was going, they'd throw it back at us.
Tear gas grenades?
Tear gas grenades.
They used...
mirrors to burn out the bulb in our TV cameras so we couldn't take pictures.
They used laser beams, I guess, to the same effect.
Rocks was their main object.
Also, we were standing at Bancroft and Telegraph inside Sprout Plaza.
And all of there was about, oh,
75 of us.
They were making a march, and they were going down Bancroft.
Well, we were not going to let them on campus.
So out of the crowd came two Molotov cocktails and caught two highway patrolmen.
And it's pretty horrible to see something like that happen.
I can see why the guys in Nam might go nuts.
They've seen it every day.
What happened to these two officers?
I have no idea.
They weren't there long enough to be friends, and they were only comrades.
Tell me about when you're in a confrontation like that, tell me about, and you see people marching on you, tell me about the feeling in the police line.
Well, you have a great feeling of comradery.
Your morale is high.
You're doing something.
You're working together.
You treat each other closer than a fellow employee.
You're almost like a brother.
You're protecting his back.
He's protecting yours.
Real good feeling.
And that is stressed in our training also.
And our morale now is built up.
We have a lag.
During idle times, morale goes down.
In busy times, morale is up.
And our present administration is busy on building the morale, taking a positive view, trying not to start rumors.
I mean, there's so many things that can lower morale.
Right, right, exactly.
And we're, as a whole unit, trying to combat it.
But we're not the only ones who start rumors.
The bad guys start them, too.
Sure, sure.
Absolutely.
Now, let's, you know, you've been out there for a number of years, and, of course, during the 60s, you listened to probably a lot of the left-wing rhetoric.
In the police force, did you men ever sit down and discuss any of the things that they were saying?
Oh, sure.
I mean, we had to.
What the hell?
We were human.
I mean, you stand out there listening to them, you can't...
They had some good ideas and they had some poor ideas.
They just had more of the poor than they did good.
But what did you feel were the good and what did you feel were the poor ideas?
Well, they wanted to build up a unity within the university, which is fine.
But on the same token, they kept tearing it down.
They really, at that time, didn't know what they wanted.
They were being led, we felt, by people other than students.
We still feel that way.
And who are these people?
Call them what you want.
Reds, communists, people that don't like universities.
I don't know.
I'd be a damn fool to put my foot in that one.
Okay.
Obviously, behavior toward demonstrations must have changed over the years.
In what way?
In the type of tactics that you would use.
Well, sure.
We used to wait for them.
I mean, we used to go into them and charge.
Now we wait for them.
And I don't know if it's better or not.
And how about the tactic?
And how about, for example, this new apartheid movement?
How have you responded?
What are the differences in the ways that you respond to that?
Well, they haven't as yet destroyed property.
Right.
They're, I'd say, 60% non-students.
Yeah.
If that many is students, 40%.
They were blocking...
passageways, the court seemed to, in Berkeley, find that they weren't guilty.
Come what may.

Now, I've read over at the Bancroft Library, I've read some American Civil Liberty Union literature on police brutality, especially during, of course, the People's Park in 1969 and the curfew and all of that.
How would you respond to that?
Well, I guess Molotov cocktails are not brutality.
So in other words, your response would be you were just responding to force.
You use reasonable force to overcome reasonable force.
Let's talk a little bit about the movement.
I saw some other flyers which dealt with disarming the police.
There was an attempt, especially in Berkeley, to disarm them.
Was there an attempt like that on campus?
There has been attempts like that over the years.
The world is full of dissidents, and they all come to Berkeley.
Well, what's the police force opinion on that?
We don't want to lose our guns.
I mean, you use your gun, you lose your gun, you lose your authority, a lot of it.
I mean, even from Wyatt Earp.
Yeah.
Because we've got little guys, too, you know, and women of small stature that...
Without the outward appearance of authority, they'd be hard pressed to take care of themselves.
That's how I feel.
I don't.
Well, that's fine.
That's all I want.
How about the relationship with the Board of Regents and the UC police?
We have nothing to do with the Regents.
We protect them.
They're the bosses.
Yeah.
But just like you, I suppose you don't know the president of the university at Texas, do you, personally?
Yeah, I know.
You know?
Yeah, but it's unusual, but usually I don't.
Yeah, same thing.
Yeah.
We know who they are, and we know they're their bosses.
Yeah, yeah.
And they've been good to us overall.
Mm-hmm.
They just gave us a new retirement package.
Oh, nice.
Is it a good one compared to... Oh, it's much better than we had.
Oh, good.
The basic rule is people can work at the university, I think, until they're 70 or 72.
You're no damn good out on the street if you're 70 or 72 as a cop.
They've dropped it down to where you can retire at age 50.
Oh, wow.
And then you get some sort of a retirement?
Oh, yeah.
And at age 55, you get 2.5%.
That's 2.5 times a year you've got.
So you can get up to 80% of your salary, which is not bad at all.
At 55, that's real nice.
Yeah, if you've got 30 years in.
How many years?
You'll have 30 years coming?
I got 34 in.
I had prior service.
Oh, I see.
Great.
Let's talk a little bit about Governor Reagan.
He's my hero.
Did the spirit go up in the force with his tough stance toward dissidents during the 1960s after he was elected?
Whoever was governor would have had to take in the same stance, I'm sure.
You can't stand by and see property destroyed, especially as considered state property, even though it is not.
It does belong to the regents, even though we do get a lot of money from the state.
Well, why do you say it is your hero, then?
No, I just like it.
Oh, okay.
Okay, let's talk a little bit about what were you?
What was your job and your responsibilities then during People's Park?
I started out, I was with the detective division, and we went down and drove stakes that says, keep off, keep out, the park is off limits, blah, blah, blah.
And as we put them in the ground, there was people behind us pulling them out.
It went from there downhill.
We put a fence around it.
They tore it down and tore up the parking lot.
By hand.
Not with picks and shovels, but by hand.
There was some asphalt there, wasn't there?
Oh, yes.
There was a lot of asphalt.
And prior to that, prior to the park, there was a business area there.
A small business area and some one-level living groups.
We went in and tore everything down, getting ready to...
I think they were probably going to build student housing there at that time.
And that just happened to be a rallying point for the dissidents to go to.
Otherwise, they'd have placed no, I don't think, any significance at all on it.
It just was a good...
Spot to go to and a good focus.
And it got everybody's attention.
It's an open space, parks, trees, babies, dogs.
And then did you help do any of the construction as far as the fence was concerned?
No.
All we did was guard it.
We guarded the people that were putting it in.
What about the fact, were you on the scene when the one character was shot and killed and the other one was blind?
I was working that day and he was a wanted felon out of another city and had been here for three days.
And he was on a roof and he was getting ready to throw a piece of concrete approximately six inches square with steel sticking out of it into a crowd of policemen.
Regardless of what you heard.
No, I mean, I've just read a number of reports, and they all conflict.
I know.
That's why I wanted your view.
I know.
It's really hard to get the answer.
But very few people want to hear our side of the view.
Well, that's why I want it.
And so he was standing up on top of which building?
Some, I don't know which one it was, down here on Telly.
Oh, it was on Telegraph.
Yeah.
I thought he was right over by the... Oh, okay, so he's probably about... Not over a block away.
Yeah, okay, about a block away.
He was not on campus.
Yeah.
Period.
Was he shot by UC or Berkeley?
No, I don't know who he was shot by.
What about the fellow that was blinded?
I thought he was blinded in the park.
When was this?
What are you talking about?
This was during the riots?
Yeah, it was about the same day, I think.
No.
The reports I read was someone was shot with a shotgun or something.
Oh, there was a number of people shot, but I don't believe that there was anybody blinded.
I might be in error, but I don't remember it.
I have another question, and that deals with just types of force that could be used.
That is, was there any debate on using things like rubber bullets that you hear about a lot today?
No, that's good today.
But if you didn't have them, you didn't hear about them.
Yeah, when did they come in?
I have no idea.
We still haven't got them.
Oh, you don't?
No.
Do you know how effective they are as far as?
I have no idea.
When did you start using shields, plexiglass shields?
On your helmets?
Mm-hmm.
First of all, I'm darned if I ever can remember, probably 65.
Yeah, probably 65.
I know maybe two years either way.
Yeah.
You don't think of these things.
I mean, as to be remembered, you're just thankful to God you got them.
And at that time, right around 65, 67, did other types of equipment come in common use that you hadn't used before?
Not that we hadn't used, no.
I mean, we'd always had our batons.
I mean, looking back, we've always had our helmets, gas masks.
We didn't get them until...
After we'd all got severely gassed two or three times.
No, not really.
No protective clothing that would be of any value to this interview.
What about no different types of boots or anything like that?
No, no.
Not like steel reinforced to protect your feet or anything like that?
No.
What about those big plexiglass shields that I've seen in pictures?
We don't have such a thing.
Oh, why not?
Because I've seen those.
You've seen them in Japan, China, but not in Berkeley.
Why not?
You don't know.
They're too cumbersome.
We had a different kind of infighting.
And we had to use physical force where it looks like to me when they use the shields, why they're using water cannons and stuff like that over there.
Yeah.
Might be the good thing.
Yeah, and they're real close, and maybe they're just pushing the crowds back.
Correct.
Yeah.
Maybe they have more respect for the police over there than they do over here.
Let's talk about that for a minute.
Do you think that, well, during the 1950s, it seems to me as a historian that there was an awful lot of respect for the police, and, of course, that shifted dramatically in the 1960s.
And it's changing again today.
Okay.
How do you think it's changing today?
It's changing where more people have more respect for the police, but it's up to the police to show something going so they can be respected for it.
We have to earn it.
It's not given to us.
What about organizations like organizations which would put out bumper stickers, support your local police and stuff?
Did you get a lot of help from... You remember those bumper stickers.
I got one probably in my memorabilia somewhere.
Did you ever get any help from that type of organization?
No.
More...
I guess moral support through people reading it, maybe.
I don't know.
But it physically didn't do us any good.
And they didn't raise money?
Not for us, they did not, no.
That's kind of interesting because they bought, you know, large, well, they handed out thousands of these bumper stickers and then they bought billboards and put things like that up.
Remember that billboard?
Yeah.
that had that little kid and it said on top, some call him pig.
But that was their limit of their help then to UC police.
I don't know what they did anywhere else, but here they didn't do nothing for us.
We didn't ask for any help.
I doubt if we would have taken it.
Right, yeah.
It might have been a conflict of interest.
Yeah.
That's interesting.
Well, let's talk a little bit about the whole idea of residency.
I read about 1971 and 72 newspapers and flyers

dealing with the Berkeley police in which they wanted the Berkeley police, they did some sort of survey and found that 85% of them didn't live in Berkeley and this and that and they wanted all of the police in Berkeley to be residents of the city and they wanted more
more community control, they called it, of police.
Did those residency changes, or did those changes down in Berkeley have any impact on the UC police?
How could they?
Well, I mean, would they... We have no room on campus to build houses.
No, I don't mean, I mean as far as Berkeley.
We could care less what Berkeley does.
But I mean as far as where you're a resident.
We have no resident regulations.
We still have two or three people who live in Berkeley.
You'd have to live in Berkeley to see the conditions to live here, so maybe that has something to do with it.
Maybe it's good, maybe it's bad.
I don't know.
Did regulations as far as hiring change?
As far as residency?
No.
Well, I can't answer for work.
I'm only saying here.
I know, I know.
Okay, it did not apply to us in any way.
Yeah, okay.
Okay, how about as far as your recruitment is concerned?
Does not apply.
Not their recruitment, I'm talking about.
Our recruitment has nothing to do with anything about residency.
Okay.
I suppose they can't live in Alaska.
It's probably too far to commute.
I know, okay.
You're getting off the whole balance.
Like I said, we had nothing to do.
with Berkeley's residency ordinance.
OK. Now, how about as far as your just basic recruitment?
How has that changed as far as equal affirmative action, equal opportunity?
We've always had it.
Oh, really?
You mean even when you started in the 50s?
Sure.
And so the proportion of women or minorities hasn't increased?
We had no women.
We had no women applying.
That is interesting.
And we now have, I don't know what you call minorities.
I suppose you're talking about, what are you talking about as minorities?
Blacks and Hispanics.
We've got blacks, Hispanics.
We've got black, Hispanic men.
We've got black and Hispanic women.
We have Asians.
We had a part Indian.
I guess we still got one of them or two.
I don't know.
But in other words, Berkeley Police Force has always been open to that.
No.
I don't have anything to do with Berkeley.
Let's forget Berkeley.
I mean, UC.
I mean, I'm at UC.
Yeah.
UC has always been an open application police department.
That is interesting.
Well, why is that?
Because Berkeley hasn't, nor had Oakland.
Oakland, I can't speak for.
I can remember when I came to work here, there was blacks on the Berkeley Police Department.
But not the proportion that there is today.
No, no.
That's really interesting.
Well, I'm about done.
Okay.
Oh, when do you feel that you're going to retire?
As soon as I feel like it.
He's been a hard guy all along.
He's been a hard guy?
Yeah.
Oh, come on.
He keeps thinking we're Berkeley.
No, no, no, I'm just getting terms mixed up.
But you think that there isn't going to be a mandatory term for you?
Sure, if I wanted to stay until I'm 70, but I don't see nothing going for me in that direction.
Whenever I feel I can't hold up my end of it, that's when I'll go.
If I can't protect the guy I'm with, there's no need of me being out there.
I hope I got sense enough to leave.
Will you donate this interview to scholarly research at Texas A&M University?
Only if it's to be used as
scholistic material, not to be published or used in any other manner.
But I could publish.
Would you allow me to publish any quotes out of this in a scholarly book?
If I could see them first, sure.
Oh, OK. OK, fine.
We're talking about student aid.
So student aid started in 1971.
And why did they start?
To act as a buffer between the police department and the university and to be seen in uniform, let the university community know we had students working as police aides.
And since then, it's mushroomed to where we have, what, 48?
41 aides now.
They're our right arm.
They dispatch, and when necessary,
They do patrol.
They do routine observation.
They take bicycle theft reports.
They do escort service.
Yeah, they do escort service, which is a very important thing.
If we have anybody that wants an escort home at night from anywhere on campus, and it seems like it's damn near anywhere in Berkeley or a mile radius, they walk them home.
Oh, great.
And they're the
They don't complain.
There's something wrong with them.
They're students.
